Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:147:* **Auditor reaction**: "Good choice." No questions raised, no novelty to justify.
Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:166:**Ubuntu LTS** (`ubuntu:24.04`): Acceptable, enterprise-familiar. Same iptables package structure as Debian. ~30 MB compressed, 5-year support (10 with Pro). Adds a layer of indirection (Canonical packaging) without adding value for a firewall-only container. Auditor reaction: "Why not Debian?"
Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:168:**Alpine Linux**: Tiny (~5 MB) but wrong for a trust boundary. Uses musl instead of glibc — introduces a variable into the exact subsystem being locked down (DNS resolution quirks in musl affect dnsmasq operation). Shorter support window (~2 years). Auditor reaction: "Why musl for a firewall container?"
Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:170:**Red Hat UBI Minimal** (`ubi9-minimal`): Strong enterprise trust aura, glibc, 10-year RHEL lifecycle. But RHEL 9 deprecates iptables in favor of nftables — a contradictory signal when the design center is careful, predictable iptables. Support requires subscription for incident response. Auditor reaction: "Trusted base, but why build new firewall logic on deprecated iptables in RHEL 9?"
Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:172:**Google Distroless**: No shell, no package manager. The sentry needs bash for startup scripts. Wrong tool for this job. Auditor reaction: "Why distroless for a control-plane utility container?"
Tools/rbk/vov_veiled/RBSIP-ifrit_pentester.adoc:174:**Wolfi / Chainguard**: Technically impressive, supply-chain-forward, glibc-based. But younger distribution without decades of iptables behavioral documentation. 12-month package retention policy conflicts with controlled versioning for a security appliance. Auditor reaction: "Interesting — justify it." That question alone disqualifies it for a trust boundary.

